Violence or #abuse is never OK. Support is available. Call 1800RESPECT on 1800 737 732 or visit https://t.co/FvWH1Y4R8z. You can speak to a trained counsellor any time of the day. #1800RESPECT https://t.co/OVg8dc2Iz1

People with #disability can be more likely to experience #abuse due to a range of factors, including reliance on other people for personal care, mobility and income. Our website contains information for people with disability to get support. https://t.co/Z0tKpFjujY

#Daisy is the free 1800RESPECT app that provides information about support services in your area. The free, easy to use app is often recommended to those impacted by #domesticviolence by sector professionals. Find out more on our website. https://t.co/NeOXuzTh8u

There are many ways to support a loved one who is experiencing #financialabuse, and #1800RESPECT can assist with advice for those in a #support role. Call 1800 737 732 or visit our website: https://t.co/xtkP3EroA3

A #safetyplan for a person with #disability needs to be developed with a support service. Issues such as communication difficulties or special care requirements can mean that extra planning and support are needed. Learn more on our website: https://t.co/LgSs3YW0Mj

The #Disability Support Toolkit has been developed to provide #sexualassault, #domesticviolence and disability frontline workers with resources to assist people who have experienced violence and abuse. https://t.co/Fk4VcuwdOQ

We invite you to subscribe to our Workers and Professionals newsletter. Updates on the #1800RESPECT service, #DVSA sector information, upcoming #conferences and more are delivered quarterly to your inbox. Winter edition out soon. Sign up via our website. https://t.co/ZmQVSrS4Nx

For many people with #disability, recognising that what they are experiencing is #abuse is a significant issue. It can be made worse by limited access to information. Our website has information on recognising forms of violence and how to access support. https://t.co/8p0CXl2mqn

Another reason why I think @DanielAndrewsMP punitive, zero empathy approach needs to change.  Distress calls to suicide hotlines up 22% in lockdown 2.0.   More compassion and less tough talk, Dan. #MaskUpMelbourne https://t.co/sa7QVWlMWi

Its restrictions and the environment it's fostered, is slowing processes down and isolating us. But all the Aus mental health sites have specific details for Covid, and I'll share a few things I've found (or some stalwarts I often fall back on).  Here we go:

If you have not had symptoms/signs of mental ill-health before, it can be hard to guage how bad it is. One good place to start is a mental health (k10) checklist. You can complete one online. Take a deep breath and give it a go:  https://t.co/PWR4VjBzXd

Lifeline and Beyond Blue both have some lists of practitioner recommendations -- but go with someone you're comfortable with, someone close, and if you're comfortable, ask mates for recs: https://t.co/BeDLvA4mXC

make yourself safe during suicide risk, one excellent way to do this is using Beyond Blue's Suicide Safety Plan app, Beyond Now. I have one, and my partner and parents can see my plan, so they know what I need when I feel suicidal. https://t.co/KUYfaBZBrF

One post-script (of many? we'll see what else I remember!): being a carer of a mentally ill person is v hard and complex. My partner gives a lot of himself to me to keep me safe and alive every day. I am encouraging him to find his own support system too: https://t.co/jZaCxO3pIb

Lifeline now runs a text service w their crisis support team, which my mate described as 'literally like texting with a friend'. The number is: 0477 13 11 14. It's a great, accessible alternative if you (understandably) do not want to/cannot call). https://t.co/u0Ir5MKdQy
